-- Danish cbank intervened in September to weaken crown, forex rise 
-- By Shida Chayesteh
-- Thu Oct 02, 2014 10:11AM EDT
-- None



COPENHAGEN, Oct 2 (Reuters) - Denmark's central bank intervened in the currency markets in September, selling 700 million Danish crowns to weaken the domestic currency, it said on Thursday.

The Danish crown, which is pegged to the euro, strengthened to a two year high that month. <EURDKK=> The central bank said its foreign currency reserves had risen to 442.4 billion Danish crowns ($75 billion) in September from 441.6 in August.